{{Infobox food | name = Ahriche | image = | caption = | alternate_name = | country = Morocco | region = Zayanes and Khénifra | national_cuisine = | creator = <!-- or | creators = --> | year = | mintime = | maxtime = | type = | course = | served = | main_ingredient = Tripe | minor_ingredient = Ganglion, caul, lung or heart | variations = | serving_size = 100 g | calories = | protein = | fat = | carbohydrate = | glycemic_index = | similar_dish = | other = }}
In [[Moroccan cuisine]], '''Ahriche''' is a dish eaten by the tribes of [[Zayanes]] and [[Khénifra]]. The name is derived from the [[Berber languages|Berber]] word for stick; this is in reference to the dish's manner of cooking. It is a dish of tripe usually consisting of ganglion, caul, lung or heart of an animal wound with intestines on a stick of oak and cooked on hot coals.
==See also== * [[List of African dishes]] * [[Berber cuisine]]
