The '''Chapel of Nossa Senhora de Baluarte''' is located on the most eastern tip of the [[Island of Mozambique]] within [[Stone Town, Mozambique|Stone Town]]. The island sits off the coast of [[Mozambique]] in [[Africa]]. The Chapel is situated outside the [[St. Sebastiao|Fort São Sebastião]] from which it can be reached through a gate.
Built by the [[Portugal|Portuguese]] in 1522, the chapel is considered to be the oldest European building in the southern hemisphere. It is also considered to be one of the finest examples of [[Manueline]] vaulted architecture in Mozambique.<ref name="Fitzpatrick2010">{{cite book|author=Mary Fitzpatrick|title=Mozambique|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_G1-nXEv7REC&pg=PA211|year=2010|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=978-1-74104-888-9|pages=211–}}</ref>
==Gallery== <gallery> Image:Nossa Senhora do Baluarte - Seaview.gif|Chapel - Seaview Image:Nossa Senhora de Baluarte - Fort view.gif|Chapel - View from Fort Image:Nossa Senhora de Baluarte - Full View.gif|Chapel - Full View Image:Chapel of Nossa Senhora de Baluarte.jpg|Chapel - View from Fort Image:Nossa Senhora de Baluarte - Entrance.gif|Chapel - Entrance Image:Nossa Senhora de Baluarte - Inside.gif|Chapel - Inside </gallery>
