{{Politics of Côte d'Ivoire}}
'''Entente of Independents of Côte d'Ivoire''' (in [[French language|French]]: ''Entente des Indépendents de Côte d'Ivoire''), a splinter group of the [[Democratic Party of Côte d'Ivoire]] (PDCI). EDICI was founded in [[Abidjan]] in the end of 1949. It was led by Vamé Doumouya and Touré Amidou. In the beginning of 1950 the [[Union of Independents of Côte d'Ivoire]] (UICI) merged into EDICI.

EDICI was fiercely pro-[[France]] and [[anticommunist]].

In 1951 EDICI merged with the [[Progressive Party of Côte d'Ivoire]] (PPCI) to form the [[Party of the French Union in Côte d'Ivoire]] (PUFCI).

Source: Gbagbo, Laurent: ''Côte d'Ivoire, Pour une alternative démocratique''. Paris: L'Harmattan, 1983.

