{{Infobox political party | name = Union of Democratic Forces of Guinea | colorcode = #00A94C | foundation = 1991 | ideology = [[Liberalism]] | international = [[Liberal International]] | country = Guinea }} The '''Union of Democratic Forces of Guinea''' ({{lang-fr|Union des forces démocratiques de Guinée}}, UFDG) is a [[liberalism|liberal]] [[political party]] in [[Guinea]].
The party was founded in 1991 by a number of opposition parties and groups. In October 2002 it was joined by a section of [[Union for Progress and Renewal (Guinea)|Union for Progress and Renewal]] under the leadership of [[Mamadou Boye Bah]], which unlike the majority of their party wanted to boycott the [[Guinean legislative election, 2002|2002 parliamentary election]]. Mamadou Ba was subsequently elected as President of UFDG. The party affiliated to the [[Republican Front for Democratic Change]] alliance, which intended to field a candidate in the [[Guinean presidential election, 2003|2003 presidential election]].<ref>''Africa South of the Sahara 2004'', p.508</ref>
From 2007 onwards the presidency of the party has been held by [[Cellou Dalein Diallo]], who stood for the party in the [[Guinean presidential election, 2010|2010 presidential election]], topping the poll in the first round before narrowly losing to [[Alpha Conde]] in the second round.
On 25 July 2015, Diallo was named as the UFDG's candidate for the [[Guinean presidential election, 2015|2015 presidential election]] at a party congress; he was also re-elected to lead the party for another five years.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/guineas-former-pm-run-presidency-october-203000084.html "Guinea's former PM to run for presidency in October"], AFP, 25 July 2015.</ref>
